* Generics for structs
* More builtin types, i128, i256, u128, u256, f128
* Identical funcion merging
* Line continuation: allow `||` and `&&` at end of line to continue expression on next line (discovered during bootstrap — multi-condition `if` is unreadable on one line)
* If-expressions / ternary: `let x = if cond { a } else { b }` (discovered during bootstrap — `let mut` + if/else is verbose boilerplate for simple conditional assignment)
* Lvalue write-through on struct-typed Optional silently drops the write. Given `class Outer { data: Inner? }` with `struct Inner { value: i32 }`, the statement `o.data!.value = 42` compiles cleanly but `println(o.data!.value)` still prints `0`. The unwrap produces an rvalue copy of the tagged struct, and the assignment lands in that copy. Either lower `expr!.field = ...` on struct optionals to a "unwrap → mutate → repack → store" sequence, or reject the lvalue form at the checker. Spec §Lvalue Unwrap and Write-Through shows exactly this struct-typed example as if it worked. Class-typed inner works correctly. (Found by Ch 3 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* Parser rejects `fn(T) -> U` function-type syntax even though spec §Composite Types calls it the canonical form (line 393). Example: `func apply(x: i32, f: fn(i32) -> i32) -> i32 { ... }` fails with `expected identifier, got PLParen (()`. Only `func(T) -> U` parses. Either teach the parser to accept `fn` as a type-position keyword, or update the spec to mark `fn` 🚧 and `func` canonical. (Found by Ch 3 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `xs.extend(ys)` is a silent no-op on slices. Spec §Built-in Methods §Slices lists `extend(other) -> unit` and §Composite Types says "In-place slice extension: `xs.extend(ys)`." Empirical: `let mut xs = [1,2,3]; xs.extend([4,5,6]); println(xs.len())` prints `3`. Same with a `.push()`-built slice. The `append(xs, elem)` built-in works (returns new slice). Either wire `extend` up, or demote in spec and provide a working in-place append-all. (Found by Ch 4 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `new_error(msg)` builtin is checker-only — no C-backend lowering. Spec §Built-in Functions §String / Conversion lists `new_error(msg): string -> error` as a stdlib shortcut, and `src/checker/checker.ly:3609` types it as `error`, but the C backend emits a literal `new_error(LYRIC_STR(...))` call with no declaration, so gcc fails with `implicit declaration of function 'new_error'` and the resulting binary won't link. The working alternative today is the stdlib class literal `Error { msg: "..." }` (compiles + runs end-to-end). Either implement the lowering (probably just sugar for `Error { msg: ... }`) or demote the entry in the spec. (Found by Ch 5 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `char_is_space` and `char_is_digit` lowering is missing in the C backend. Compiling a tokenizer that uses them emits `c_backend: unhandled builtin: char_is_space` / `char_is_digit` warnings and the generated C contains lines like `bool _t4 = ;` (assignment with empty RHS), which gcc rejects. The other `char_is_*` predicates listed in spec §Built-in Functions probably need an audit too. The functions are typed correctly by the checker — just the lowerer never grew an arm for them. Blocks the Ch 4 tokenizer example from compiling end-to-end. (Found by Ch 5 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* Bare `return` inside `main()` fails to compile in C. The C backend lowers `func main()` as `int main(int _argc, char** _argv)` (so it can accept the CLI args the runtime injects), but a Lyric `return` with no value lowers to a bare `return;`, which gcc rejects with `'return' with no value, in function returning non-void`. Either lower bare `return` inside `main` as `return 0;`, or pick a void-returning C entry point and have the runtime shim handle argc/argv. Workaround in the book: restructure with `if`/`else` instead of early `return`. (Found by Ch 5 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* Interface dispatch on `error`-typed values is broken in the C backend. Calling `e.message()` where `e: error` (e.g. from a `(T, error)` destructure) compiles through checker but the generated C declares `e` as `const char*` (the legacy string-as-error representation) and then calls `Error_message((const char*)e)` against the concrete-Error signature `Error_message(Error*)`. gcc rejects with "incompatible types". `f"{e}"` works because f-string interpolation has a special-cased lowering for `error`. Fix: either model `error` as a proper interface vtable (so `e.message()` dispatches dynamically) or, at minimum, recognize `Error` as the sole concrete impl and downcast in the lowerer. Until this is fixed, the book teaches `f"{e}"` for stringifying errors, not `e.message()`. (Found by Ch 5 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* f-string interpolation of an `error` value bypasses user-defined `message()`. Given a custom error `class ParseError { line: i32, col: i32, msg: string; pub func message(self) -> string { return f"{self.line}:{self.col}: {self.msg}" } }` and a value `e: error` holding a `ParseError`, `println(f"err: {e}")` prints just the `msg` field ("unexpected end of input") instead of the formatted "3:7: unexpected end of input" the `message()` override would produce. The lowerer special-cases `{error_value}` to pull the `msg` field directly (treating all errors as the concrete `Error` class), so structural-subtype `message()` overrides are silently ignored. Related to the `e.message()` C-backend bug — both stem from `error` not being modeled as a true interface with dynamic dispatch. (Found by Ch 5 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* Generic class methods that access `self.<field>` lower to a null receiver in the C backend. Example: `class Stack<T> { items: [T]; pub func push(self, item: T) { self.items.push(item) } }` instantiated as `let mut s = Stack<f64> { items: empty }; s.push(1.0)` compiles through check/lower/mono but the emitted C reads `lyric_push(&/* null value */->items, item, LyricSlice_double);` — the receiver pointer is dropped on the floor inside the monomorphized method body. Same failure shape for read access in `pop`/`peek` (`lyric_pop(&/* null value */->items)`). Non-generic classes work fine; the bug is specific to monomorphized methods on generic classes. Also: `Stack<f64> { items: [] }` (untyped empty slice literal) fails earlier with `validateAllExprsResolved: TypeVar leak 'T'` — the empty literal does not unify with the class's `T`. Workaround for the latter: `let empty: [f64] = []; let s = Stack<f64> { items: empty }`. Until this is fixed, the book's Ch 6 `Stack<T>` example is illustrative-only with a 🚧 callout. (Found by Ch 6 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `(T, error)` tuple destructure inside a method that itself returns `(T, error)` generates malformed C when the call is recursive. Repro: in `Parser.parse_primary(self) -> (f64, error)`, replacing `let val = self.parse_expr()?` with `let (val, err) = self.parse_expr(); if err != null { return (0.0, err) }` causes the C backend to emit `double val = _t14;` and `const char* err = _t14;` where `_t14` is of type `LyricResult_double` (the tuple-return temp). gcc rejects with "incompatible types when initializing type 'double' using type 'LyricResult_double'". The non-recursive destructure form works (e.g. in `main()` calling `parse()`), and the `?` form on the recursive call works. So the bug is the combination of (a) destructuring a `(T, error)` return, (b) inside a method whose own return type is `(T, error)`, (c) when the called method is `self.<recursive>`. The lowerer is reusing the tuple-temp slot directly instead of unpacking it into the named locals. Workaround: use `?` instead of explicit destructure for self-recursive `(T, error)` calls. (Found by Ch 7 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* ~~`assert(cond, msg)` and `assert_eq(actual, expected, msg?)` builtins are silently dropped by the C backend~~ **FIXED 2026-06-21 (Bill + Hewitt).** Root cause: not the lowerer (the lowerer was correctly emitting `ExBuiltin` for assert/assert_eq); it was the optimizer's dead-temp pass — `is_side_effect_expr` didn't list `assert`, `assert_eq`, `panic`, so their unit-typed result temps got dropped before reaching the C backend. Three names added to `src/optimizer/optimizer.ly` `is_side_effect_expr`. Also: the runtime macros use `longjmp(_lyric_test_jmp, ...)` which segfaults when assert fires outside a test runner. Added `_lyric_test_active` static flag in `src/c_backend/c_backend.ly`: set to 1 around `setjmp` in the test runner, the macros now `longjmp` if active and `exit(1)` otherwise. Bootstrap reaches fixed point; suite is 82/89 PASS (was 86/89 — 4 previously silent fails now correctly surface, including the optional-struct-writeback bug Ch 3 reviser logged separately).
* `final func` fires twice when `destroy()` is called explicitly on a stack-local class. Repro: `class Connection { name: string; final func cleanup(self) { println(f"closing {self.name}") } }; func main() { let c = Connection { name: "db" }; c.destroy() }` prints `closing db` twice — once from the explicit `c.destroy()` and once again on scope-exit cleanup of the now-freed slot. Either (a) the explicit `destroy()` should mark the slot so scope-exit doesn't re-fire `cleanup`, or (b) `final` should be one-shot via a guard flag on the class header (`if already_finaled return`). Without `c.destroy()` the function fires exactly once on scope exit, so the workaround is to omit the explicit destroy when using `final` for resource cleanup. (Spec §Class Destruction documents the order as `final → auto-destructor → slab free` but doesn't say `final` is one-shot or re-entrant.) Found by Ch 8 book reviser, 2026-06-21.
* Default-method method-call syntax doesn't resolve in the checker. Spec §Default Methods promises that an interface body like `pub func count_edges(graph: G) -> i32 { ... }` (inside `interface Graph<G, N, E>`) is "Callers invoke it via method syntax (`graph.count_edges()`)". Empirical: `g.count_edges()` for `g: SimpleGraph` with a working `impl Graph<SimpleGraph, SimpleNode, SimpleEdge>` block fails with `checker: unknown method: count_edges`. The free-function form `count_edges<SimpleGraph, SimpleNode, SimpleEdge>(g)` resolves correctly and runs end-to-end (as in `testdata/interfaces.ly`). Either wire method-syntax dispatch for default methods on every interface type parameter, or demote the spec line to 🚧. (Found by Ch 9 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* Label-prefixed default methods don't get injected for user-defined hints. Spec §Default Methods Are Label-Prefixed says `relation MyList Panel:w owns [Widget:p]` over `interface MyList<P, C>` should generate `panel.w_add(widget)` and `panel.w_count()`. Empirical: with `pub func P.add(self, child: C) { ... }` or `pub func add(parent: P, child: C) { ... }` inside `MyList`, neither `panel.add(w1)`, `panel.w_add(w1)`, nor any other receiver-style call resolves — `checker: unknown method` for every spelling. Additionally, the abstract `field P.items: [C]` declared in the interface is not visible inside the default method body when accessed as a direct field (`parent.items` → `field items not found on type`); only the getter/setter form (`parent.items()` / `parent.set_items(...)`) resolves. The stdlib hints (`ArrayList`, `DoublyLinked`, `HashedList`) *do* get label-prefixed methods on the parent (`team.roster_append(p)`, `dir.files_append(f)`) — that machinery is implemented specifically for the three stdlib hints, not as a generic feature of the relation desugar. Either generalize the relation-desugar to inject label-prefixed methods for any binary interface used as a hint (the spec's stated intent), or narrow the spec to say only the three stdlib hints get method injection today, with the rest of the family on the roadmap. (Found by Ch 9 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `self: P` typed parameter is rejected by the parser inside interface default methods. Repro: `interface MyList<P, C> { pub func add(self: P, child: C) { ... } }` fails with `expected identifier, got PColon (:)` at the `:` after `self`. Workarounds: (a) receiver-binding form `pub func P.add(self, child: C)` (self is implicitly typed), or (b) plain top-level `pub func add(parent: P, child: C)`. Worth either teaching the parser to accept `self: T` as a regular typed parameter (matching the receiver-binding semantics) or documenting in spec that `self` is only valid as the implicit first param of a `Type.method` declaration. (Found by Ch 9 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* String-keyed Dict literal `{"key": value}` is rejected by the parser. Spec §Standard Library Reference §Dict<K,V> promises three key forms for Dict literals — backtick syms (`` {`alice`: 1} ``), string literals (`{"NYC": 8_000_000}`), and integer literals (`{1: "one"}`) — and says "the parser disambiguates Dict literals from struct literals by the first key form." Empirical: backtick and integer keys parse and run end-to-end against the stdlib `Dict` (verified Ch 10 reviser); the string-keyed form fails with `expected PRParen, got SEOF ()` — the parser appears to commit to a struct-literal interpretation when the opening token is a string, then trips trying to close it. Either teach the dict-literal disambiguator to recognize the `{"<string-literal>":` prefix as a Dict opener, or demote string-keyed literals in the spec. Today, string-keyed dicts must be built with `Dict<string, V>()` plus explicit `.set(...)` calls. (Found by Ch 10 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `Dict.length()` vs `Dict.len()` naming mismatch between spec and stdlib. Spec §Standard Library Reference §Dict<K,V> lists the method as `len() -> i32`, but `stdlib/std.ly:599` defines `pub func Dict.length<K, V>(self) -> i32 where K: Hashable { return self.d_hash_count }` — there is no `len()` method on `Dict` today, only `length()`. Calling `d.len()` fails with `checker: unknown method: len`. Either rename the stdlib method to `len()` (matches the rest of the stdlib's `xs.len()` convention for slices/strings) or update the spec table. The carry-forward §Idiomatic Lyric stance is `xs.len()` everywhere, so renaming `Dict.length` → `Dict.len` is the consistent fix. The book Ch 10 uses `keys.len()` on the returned slice (which works) and avoids `d.length()` / `d.len()` in code examples until this is resolved. (Found by Ch 10 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `Dict<K, V>` as a non-generic class field leaks the inner typevar `V` at the checker. Repro: `class VarTable { vars: Dict<Sym, f64> }` plus `pub func VarTable.set_var(self, name: string, value: f64) { self.vars.set(sym(name), value) }` and `pub func VarTable.get_var(self, name: string) -> (f64, error) { let entry = self.vars.get(sym(name)); ... }` fails with `checker: validateAllExprsResolved: TypeVar leak 'V' in VarTable.get_var at <pos>:9:29`. The same code paths work end-to-end when the `Dict<Sym, f64>` is a local in `main` instead of a field on a non-generic class — so the bug is in how field types propagate concrete type arguments to the generic where-clause methods (`Dict.get<K, V>(self, key: K) -> DictEntry<K, V>? where K: Hashable`) when the receiver is field-of-self. Making the outer class generic (`class VarTable<V> { vars: Dict<Sym, V> }`) trips a *different* downstream failure: `c_backend[c_type/TyClassHandle]: unmangled generic class 'Dict' reached c_backend ... monomorphizer missed a TyClassHandle site`. Either fix the checker to propagate field-position type arguments into method-typevars, or fix the monomorphizer to walk into generic-class field types of generic outer classes. Workaround in the book Ch 10: teach `Dict<Sym, f64>` as a local in `main` (not as a class field) for the variable-bindings example, with a 🚧 callout. (Found by Ch 10 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* The ai_callback_dekay for WaitForAgent was not working in the most recen tsession.
* Imiports should be loaded recursively
* Qualified type names and qualified enum variants don't resolve across `import`. Today `import lexer` makes `lexer.tokenize(...)` (a qualified *function call*) work, but every qualified *type* reference fails — `let xs: [lexer.Token] = []` fails the checker with `unknown struct/class: lexer.Token`, `lexer.Token { kind: 1, value: "x" }` (qualified constructor) fails the same way, and `lexer.TokenKind.Plus` (qualified enum variant) fails the same way. The prefix-then-merge import resolver in `src/ast/modules.ly` rewrites qualified call sites (`ExFnCall` with a module-prefixed callee) but doesn't handle `TyHandle`, struct-literal `kind`, or enum-variant resolution against an imported namespace. Workaround in book Ch 13: expose constructor *functions* from packages (e.g. `pub func new_point(...) -> Point`) and let callers stay typed structurally — `let p = mylib.new_point(1, 2)` infers `Point` from the return type and never names it. Real fix: the qualified-name resolver should produce the same prefixed identifier (`lexer_Token`, `lexer_TokenKind_Plus`) whether it's a call, a type annotation, a struct-literal opener, or an enum-variant access. This is the single biggest gap in the current module system — it forces the Lyric compiler itself to skip `import` entirely and rely on flat-namespace merging of `BOOTSTRAP_FILES`. (Found by Ch 13 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* `let mut xs: [ImportedType] = []` leaks the imported type name at the checker even after `import` resolution. The annotation `[ast.Token]` is rejected with both `unknown struct/class: ast.Token` and `validateAllExprsResolved: TypeVar leak 'ast.Token'` — same root cause as the qualified-type bug above, but worth a separate mention because it surfaces *only* when you annotate the empty-slice literal. Workaround: build the slice with a seed element and pop it (`let seed = ast.new_token(...); let mut tokens = [seed]; tokens.pop()`), or fold the type lookup into the constructor function. Once qualified type resolution lands, the annotation form should just work. (Found by Ch 13 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* Bare `import "path"` (string-literal path with no alias) crashes the resolver. Spec §Imports and the language reference both call this out as a known crasher; the parser accepts the form but the resolver has no codepath to derive an alias from the path basename. Either implement basename-derived aliasing (`import "parser/v2"` → alias `v2`) or reject at parse time with a clear "give it an alias" message. Workaround: always use `import alias from "path"`. (Found by Ch 13 book reviser, 2026-06-21 — long-standing, just confirming.)
* CLI: there is no `-mod` flag on `lyric compile`. The book's pre-edit Ch 13 §13.3 showed `lyric compile -mod .`, which fails with `error: cannot read -mod`. Reality: directory mode is automatic — `lyric compile <dir>` checks for `<dir>/lyric.mod`, and `lyric compile <single.ly>` checks for `<parent>/lyric.mod`. Either add a `-mod <path>` flag for explicit module-root specification (useful when the project root isn't a parent of the input file) or update the spec to remove the flag mention. The auto-detection is fine; only the docs are out of sync. (Found by Ch 13 book reviser, 2026-06-21.)
* ~~Make `OwningList` and `RefList` private in the stdlib.~~ **FIXED 2026-06-21 (Bill + Hewitt, commits ec083de + 1e376f1).** Resolution went further than "make private": `OwningList`, `RefList`, `RefArrayList`, and `ArrayListBase` were all eliminated. `DestructorBlock` gained a `kind: RelationKind` field; the parser accepts `destructor owns P/C { ... }` and `destructor refs P/C { ... }` (bare `destructor P` defaults to `owns` for backward compat); the destructor-desugar pass filters `db.kind == rel.kind`. Stdlib collapsed to three user-facing hints (`ArrayList`, `DoublyLinked`, `HashedList`) each carrying paired owns/refs destructor blocks. Three pre-existing latent bugs fixed as a side effect: `relation ArrayList X refs [Y]` no longer silently cascades; `relation DoublyLinked X owns [Y]` no longer silently leaks; `relation DoublyLinked X refs [Y]` works. Testdata migrated (testdata/owning_list.ly + ref_list.ly + destroy_shared.ly now use `DoublyLinked owns/refs`). Bootstrap fixed point holds; suite is exactly the 82/89 baseline.
* ~~`embed` desugar copies methods, contradicting spec §Interface Embedding.~~ **FIXED 2026-06-21 (Bill + Hewitt).** The method-copy loop in `desugar_interface_embeds` (`src/desugar/desugar.ly`, the `for m in parent_iface.im_children()` block) was deleted; the pass docstring updated to call out the spec contract. `testdata/test_desugar.ly::test_embed_does_not_copy_methods` (previously failing with "embed must NOT copy methods") now passes. Suite went from 82/89 to 83/89 — no other test perturbed because (a) the post-collapse stdlib hints carry their own paired destructors directly and never `embed`, and (b) user code that relied on the over-copy already didn't work end-to-end thanks to the separate label-prefixed-default-methods bug. Book Ch 9.6 + §Three Passes refreshed to drop the 🚧 over-copy callout.
* ~~`embed` keyword removed entirely.~~ **DONE 2026-06-21 (Bill + Hewitt).** Phase 2 of the multi-class interface redesign (`cr/docs/multi-class-interface-redesign.md` §9). With OwningList/RefList already collapsed into DoublyLinked (commit `1e376f1`), `embed` had no remaining users in the stdlib or compiler. Deleted from lexer (KEmbed token + keyword dict entry), parser (interface-body case, `parse_interface_embed`, identifier-fallback case), AST (`class InterfaceEmbed`, `relation ArrayList InterfaceDecl:ie owns [InterfaceEmbed:ie]`, `relation ArrayList InterfaceEmbed:ie_arg owns [TypeExpr:ie_arg]`, two transitive-embed pull-in loops in MergeStdlib), desugar (`desugar_interface_embeds` pass and its `desugar_all` call site), checker (impl-block-satisfaction-by-embedding fallback), lowerer (`embeds: [string]` field on LInterfaceDecl + the rename-prefix loop that consulted it), LIR (`embeds` field), main pretty-printer (embeds emission block). Also deleted `testdata/embed.ly` and three `test_embed_*` cases in `test_desugar.ly`; golden updated to 9 PASS. Spec §Interface Embedding deleted, hard-keyword list updated, soft-reserved list updated, §Recently Removed gained an entry. Book Ch 9.6 rewritten to a user-defined `Stack` hint example (declaring its own paired destructors directly), Ch 9.9 pipeline list updated to five passes (InterfaceFields → FieldAccess → Relations → Destructors → DefaultImpls), App A keyword table + glossary cleaned. Bootstrap fixed point holds at 113,883 lines (down from 114,624 — 741 lines saved). Suite is the same 82/88 baseline as before (6 known pre-existing fails: concat, global_dict_rc, graph, lock, optional_struct_writeback, tree).
* Move `owns`/`refs` annotation from `RelationDecl` onto `ImplBlock`, eliminating `RelationDecl` post-desugar. Design rationale (Bill + Hewitt, 2026-06-22): with labels-on-impl-type-vars landed (commits `91b1d06` + `56eab35`, redesign §3.8), the only thing keeping `RelationDecl` as a distinct AST node downstream of desugar is the `owns`/`refs` flag. If we add `kind: RelationKind?` to `ImplBlock` and let it carry the ownership semantics, three desugar passes (`desugar_interface_fields`, `desugar_destructors`, `desugar_relations`) all converge on iterating `block.ib_children()` instead of `block.rd_children()`. After `desugar_relations` collapses every `RelationDecl` into a labeled+annotated impl, the relation node is purely transient — never seen by checker/lowerer/c_backend. Syntax: `impl Hint<A:l1, B:l2> owns { ... }` — single `owns`/`refs` keyword between the closing `>` and the opening `{` (mirrors `relation X A:l1 owns [B:l2]` exactly). Two big architectural payoffs beyond the consolidation: (a) the hint-shape interface concept stops being a stdlib-exclusive privilege held by ArrayList/DoublyLinked/HashedList — any interface that declares `field T.name: Type` + `destructor T { ... }` blocks can be the target of an `owns`/`refs`-annotated impl, and the existing Phase 3a validator (`validate_relation_hints`) generalizes from "is this used as a relation hint" to "is this used as an owns/refs-annotated impl" with the same three rules; (b) it unblocks user-defined hints as genuinely first-class. Cost estimate: ~1.5× the 56eab35 commit — AST gains a small field, parser-trivial, desugar passes switch iteration target (substantial), checker generalizes validator scope (small). Phase 3c-capability (dotted-scope call form) is intentionally landing BEFORE this work because it's the user-visible payoff of the original sprint; this cleanup is hygiene that should follow but not block. When picked up: write a doc-only commit first describing `RelationDecl` post-desugar collapse, then implementation, then bootstrap fixed-point check. (Found 2026-06-22 while designing labels-on-impl-type-vars; deferred to keep Phase 3c-capability unblocked.)
* ~~Move `owns`/`refs` annotation from `RelationDecl` onto `ImplBlock`.~~ **DONE 2026-06-22 (Bill + Hewitt).** Shipped as redesign §3.9 across commits `cdcb638` (docs), `8523609` (parser: ImplBlock.kind slot + owns/refs token-peek), `aa0e681` (desugar pass 3 split: Phase A relation→impl skeleton, Phase B impl-driven field injection & mappings), `e617655` (desugar pass 4 destructors iterate impls), `5361641` (checker Phase 1.6 validator iterates impls), `6b96125` (testdata acceptance test). User-authored `impl MyHint<A, B> owns { }` over a user-defined hint interface now injects fields and synthesizes destructors with no relation needed — empirically verified by `testdata/test_owns_on_impl.ly` (3 tests: user-defined hint owns, user-defined hint refs, relation-surface regression). Bootstrap fixed point at 114,529 LOC; suite at 84/90 PASS (was 83/89). Architectural side effect: `RelationDecl` is now purely transient in the AST — never observed by checker, lowerer, LIR, monomorphizer, or c_backend. The relation keyword stays as the daily-driver spelling for class ownership.
* Slice invalidation during mid-iteration `array_append` on a child collection. Found 2026-06-22 while implementing §3.9 Phase B. Snapshotting `existing_mappings = impl_block.ibm_children()` before a loop that calls `array_append<ImplBlock, ImplMapping>(impl_block, m)` works for small interfaces (ArrayList: 3 fields, no realloc) but segfaults for larger ones (HashedList: 6 fields, triggers realloc partway through; the snapshot becomes a dangling slice header pointing into freed backing storage). Workaround: buffer additions into a local slice and append after the iteration completes (the pattern now used in `desugar_relations` Phase B). Fix options: (a) document this realloc-invalidation rule in the language reference's Slices section so users don't trip on it, (b) make iteration over a class's relation-children grab a copy of the slice header before yielding so the body's mutations don't invalidate it, or (c) make `array_append` against an actively-iterated collection a checked runtime error in `--detect-uaf` builds. Today the only visible symptom is a segfault with no useful diagnostic.
* Module-level `let x: ConcreteClass = ConcreteClass { ... }` miscompiles to uninitialized `_t0` in C output. Found 2026-06-22 while writing `testdata/test_owns_on_impl.ly`. Repro: `class DestroyCount { n: i32 }; let destroyed: DestroyCount = DestroyCount { n: 0 }` at module top-level produces `static DestroyCount* destroyed = _t0;` in the generated C, where `_t0` is never defined (the temporary that should hold the class allocation is emitted inside main() rather than at file scope). gcc fails with `'_t0' undeclared here (not in a function)`. Workaround used: drop the module-level state and pass shared counters as function parameters (or restructure the test to not need one). Either lift the initialization expression into a generated module-init function and call it from main(), or restrict module-level `let` to value types (primitives/structs/tuples) until the lifter is in place.

* Phase 3c-capability dotted-scope sugar doesn't accept hard keywords as
  label names — `obj.where.children()` fails to parse because `where`
  lexes as `KWhere` everywhere. The flat textual-prefix form
  `obj.where_children()` works fine. Affected labels among today's relation
  declarations: `where` (FuncDecl:where → WhereClause).
  Fix options: (a) parser accepts hard-keyword tokens in scope-label
  position (after `.`, followed by `.`/`(`); (b) rename the offending
  relation labels to non-keywords. (a) is the principled fix; (b) is a
  one-line ast.ly edit. Tracked because Phase 3d's checker.ly migration
  was forced to keep `.where_children()` flat for 3 sites while migrating
  77 other sites successfully.

* ~~Phase 3c-capability dotted-scope sugar doesn't accept hard keywords~~
  **RESOLVED 2026-06-22**: chose KISS — hard keywords are reserved
  everywhere, no carve-outs. Renamed `:where` label to `:wc` in ast.ly
  (6 call sites swept across checker/lowerer/ast/main) and renamed
  `:from` to `:src` in testdata/interfaces.ly (3 call sites). Tightened
  `parse_relation_side` to require `LIdent` for labels, matching
  `parse_impl`. Suite stays at 84/6/0/90.

* Future: raw-identifier escape syntax (e.g. `\where` or `` `where` ``)
  to let users actually use hard keywords as identifiers in any name
  position — field names, label names, scope-access, variable names.
  Today the language reserves all 36 hard keywords absolutely. The
  empirical pain point this would address: forced renames like
  `:where` → `:wc` lose semantic information in user-visible AST
  access paths. Low priority — the bootstrap source is the only
  significant codebase, and it has 0 other keyword-collision sites.

* ~~Phase 3e — drop the textual-prefix emission~~ **DONE 2026-06-22 (Bill + Hewitt).** Shipped option (ii): labeled relation-injected storage names are mangled with a `__` prefix (`Team.__roster_children`, methods `team.__roster_append`, etc.) so the bare-flat textual-prefix form is unreachable. The dotted-scope sugar from Phase 3c-capability (`team.roster.children`, `team.roster.append(p)`) is now the only user-visible access path. Bill flipped the recommendation from option (i) — checker rejection with a marker field — to option (ii) by asking what happens when a user declares a field that collides with the textual-prefix name; with mangling, the two live in disjoint namespaces by construction and coexist freely. Eight generation sites updated consistently (desugar field injection, desugar destructor-body method rename × 2, checker labeled method registration × 2, checker dotted-rewrite target × 2, monomorphizer late specialization). The monomorphizer's last-underscore split logic that recovers the label from a registered name was patched to skip the leading `__` so it doesn't absorb the mangling into the label and double-prefix. Pre-existing Phase 3d sweep stragglers fixed: `stdlib/std.ly` had one bare-flat `self.d_hash_count`; ten testdata files (arraylist, destroy_shared, hashed_list, interfaces, method_iface, owning_list, ref_list, test_impl_type_arg_labels, test_owns_on_impl, test_parser) needed migration. Two test files had user-authored `impl X { P.field <-> Class.<label>_<field> }` bindings that named the now-mangled storage; those bindings were redundant with Phase B's auto-generated mappings and were deleted. Acceptance test `testdata/test_phase3e_user_namespace.ly` verifies that `class Team { roster_children: i32 }` (user-declared) coexists with `relation ArrayList Team:roster owns [...]` (scope-injected `__roster_children`) — both reachable, both mutable, no collision. Bootstrap fixed point at 114,513 lines (was 114,573). Suite 85 PASS / 6 FAIL / 91 TOTAL (added the acceptance test). The 6 baseline fails are unchanged.

* Checker-level rejection of bare-flat access to mangled scope-injected
  names. Today (post-Phase-3e) bare-flat access like `team.roster_children`
  is rejected at the gcc layer with "did you mean `__roster_children`?".
  This is serviceable but happens late. A checker rule that recognizes a
  mangled storage name in the receiver type and rejects bare-flat access
  with the Lyric-level suggestion "use team.roster.children" would give
  a cleaner error one stage earlier. Low priority — gcc's hint is good
  enough for now.
